Someone has suggested I use a portion of my return for a vacation and I'll be honest, I kinda forgot those existed.

To be honest, I kind of just want a hug because I'm growing more and more exhausted with every historical event that seems to happen every 8 months. I'm just beaten down and demoralized and it's starting to take a toll.
I genuinely believe that violence isn't the solution but at the same time there are some people who deserve a slap across the face to knock a few brain cells loose.

I think a lot of this can be summed up to poor direction, writing and an overall short-sighted view of what the series should've been. This was a risk from the beginning since Cowboy Bebop is an evergreen anime that is held up as a shining example of the animated medium.

5) By humanizing Vicious they effectively removed all the mystique and terror he represents. He became a hapless idiot, jealous of other people's success and so narcissistic that he was unappealing. It was just pathetic and sad, not badass or terrifying.

4) Ed. Just... No. I am so happy that they embraced the non-binary aspect of Ed by casting Eden Perkins but that performance was... No. It was so unbelievable even within the universe the show established.

3) Daniella Pineda, as far as I'm concerned, did not play Faye Valentine. Faye Valentine is a femme fatale and the character Daniella played was a spoiled brat who was in your face for the sake of being in your face. She lacked that suave smugness Faye is famous for.

2) Mustafa Shakir was the best part of the show but they really did his character dirty by adding superfluous family drama, dumbing him down to become a "deadbeat dad." Also the "black male" line directed towards him was so cringey and distasteful.

1) John Cho, while a fantastic actor who I think captured the essence of Spike, was not capable of playing such a physical character, especially one who is supposed to be a master of Jeet Kune Do who  dances around opponents while fighting. He has never shown those skills.

Comedy is tough. Telling jokes is tough. I firmly believe that there shouldn't be a joke you tell to one group and not another. Punching down is the least of comedy, the laziest kind. Punch up and knock the crowns off the kings, don't knock the bowls out of peasants hands.

Lots of people are like that tho, they just know what they think is funny and tell the same jokes in all crowds and wonder why people didn't laugh that hard about their joke this time than the last time.

Not to say people shouldn't be able to tell jokes. Jokes are part of human interaction, and I think comedy should always be the last bastion of free speech. But trying to do a trans joke around trans people is a case of "know your audience"

I think people are starting to realize that sometimes joking is good and sometimes it is bad. The most important skills in joke telling is timing and reading the room. If you can't do those then don't tell the joke.
